    "user_reviews": [
      {
        "text": "Uses a 12v hpwr connector but a braided 3*PCI-E adaptor of good quality is supplied in the box.\n\nThe aesthetics of the card are magic, the cover plate on the back attaches magnetically and hides your power (and ARGB!) cables via the back rather than having to route them over the top. This should avoid connector tension issues.\n\nThe lattice at the top is alloy, of good quality. The RGB is subtle along the top and not distracting in a vertical mount.\n\nThe card performs well stock and mine responded well to undervolting and memory tweaks. The cooler is quite capable of keeping temperatures to sensible levels. Make no mistake however this cooler is very large and this card is a true triple slot.",
        "user_name": "KFX",
        "source": "msy.com.au",
        "rating": 5,
        "date": "7 months ago",
        "icon": "https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/shsm/AGYqVK3c3i73ivHdLBwXQA3WETkidgjL9bYGvQ62cMTPWFTa5A1asxuX4n_QGn2G_UcIJLIMoA=w40-h40-c0x00000000-cc"
      },
      {
        "text": "I have had this for about a month and a half and is used most days for gaming, so about time for a review.\nI watched several comparison videos before grabbing this GPU and it was always in the top two or three of the 9070 XT models. I'll focus on what i saw as common questions in comments about the design from a user perspective as the benchmarks are widely available.\n- Yes this card does use the newer 16pin connector, but as it draws much less power than the 50 series which were having melting problems, this should not influence your buying decision when it comes to any 9070 XT, so not a concern for this card.\n- The biggest appeal of this card to me (aside from the good performance and thermals) is the 'hidden' connector setup. I had reservations about the bending of the cable to fit, however i can say it actually needs only a VERY gentle curve due to the wide recess it sits in, and would be less of a bend than the traditional edge connections would usually have, so again nothing to be concerned with there. It also allows you to take the main power cable and an aRGB cable straight out from the motherboard-facing edge of the GPU and through the case cable slots which on an ATX mobo compatible case lined up perfectly, so it's an incredibly clean design, i really hope more manufacturers do this!\n- The magnetic backplate which covers the cables and socket, does sit over the back of the chip and i was wondering how much it would add to the heat buildup. However taking it on and off seems to make no noticeable difference to the temps (maybe a degree? hard to say unless i turned off the case fans in total, which you wouldn't want to do anyway), but this was something i also had reservations about and am happy to say any difference is insignificant. It does provide a very clean and classy look and is well worth it given that it doesn't adversely affect the cooling.\n- I think the colour might be divisive to some wanting a subtle looking GPU when viewing it on the webpage. In reality it is a light 'warm' pewter grey, and it looks much less gold coloured in person than i thought it would, it's closer to a brushed nickel/pewter look and while different, i feel it still blends very well with the black and dark grey you might have in your PC case.\n- the included anti-sag bracket is functional and fairly unobtrusive. Its a single flat bar with an adjustable rubber seat at the tip and fits 'below' the card (on the GPU fan side/bottom side). It attaches to the same thumbscrews over top of the card mounting slot screwholes. It takes up about a single slot 'width' which may be a concern if you wanted to put another card of any type in the slot right next to the GPU.\n- Have had no problems at all with drivers or the AMD software (this is my first AMD card, usually had team green but pretty unimpressed with their choices lately)\n- For context around size and colours of this card i've added some photos of my build. My card is installed in a Fractal North XL (white) case (replaced the fans with Fractals RGB models tho), on a Asus ROG Strix X870E-E Gaming Wifi mobo, with a Phanteks Glacier One 360 M25G2 (black with RGB) AIO, the PSU cables are the standard newer black Corsair ones. The inside of these cases is a dark grey and the rubber grommets are 'standard' black, so hopefully that helps getting a feel for how it'll look in yours!\n\nOverall really happy with this card, i will definitely look for Sapphire brand GPUs again that's for sure",
        "user_name": "TristanL956",
        "source": "pbtech.co.nz",
        "rating": 5,
        "date": "a year ago",
        "icon": "https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/shsm/AGYqVK1iOjN7M-0EQ4S6tZ3cCk_3g4Yms4ULhv45gC9gF56wx5nwxflgfZ1KkPQT06iyRdXyQA=w40-h40-c0x00000000-cc"
      },
      {
        "title": "Top Tier",
        "text": "Fastest of the 9070XT. Stable with such a clean look, magnetic backplate, and the hidden wires are actually a necessity considering the size of the card. Very happy with this purchase! Redstone takes this card to a new level with excellent performance in 4k. Coil whine is present but expected under the load I have presented to this card during workstation tasks. Newegg was the shipping party and has excellent support with the MOST bland shipping box of which I was very thankful. Cut up the front panel of my 680X because push/pull is required in my case with the 360 Rad for optimal cooling.",
